.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm libxaes256gcm
library implements XAES-256-GCM, an extended-nonce authenticated encryption
with associated data (AEAD) algorithm, and its key-committing variant
KC-XAES-256-GCM.
.Pp
Both variants are compatible with NIST standards and can be considered a
composition of key derivation using the standard CMAC-based KDF and
AES-256-GCM.
.Pp
The 192-bit nonce makes random nonces safe to use, avoiding the catastrophic
consequences of nonce reuse that affect AES-256-GCM with 96-bit nonce.
.Pp
The key-committing variant binds each ciphertext to one specific key,
preventing attacks where an adversary can generate a single ciphertext that
decrypts successfully under multiple keys into different plaintexts.
.Pp
The following constants are defined:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Dv XAES256GCM_KEY_SIZE
Key length in bytes (32).
.It Dv XAES256GCM_NONCE_SIZE
Nonce length in bytes (24).
.It Dv XAES256GCM_OVERHEAD
Ciphertext overhead in bytes: the 16-byte authentication tag.
.It Dv XAES256GCM_KC_OVERHEAD
Ciphertext overhead in bytes for the key-committing variant: the 16-byte
authentication tag plus a 32-byte key commitment tag (48 bytes total).
.It Dv XAES256GCM_AAD_MAX
Maximum size of associated data in bytes (minimum of 2^61 - 1 and SIZE_MAX).
.It Dv XAES256GCM_PLAINTEXT_MAX
Maximum size of plaintext in bytes (minimum of 2^36 - 32 and SIZE_MAX - 48).
.El
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_init
initializes the XAES-256-GCM context
.Fa c
with the 32-byte secret
.Fa key .
.Pp
Each seal and open operation is semantically independent,
but the context is not thread-safe: each thread should use its own context.
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_destroy
disposes of the context
.Fa c .
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_seal
encrypts and authenticates
.Fa plaintext
of length
.Fa plaintext_len ,
authenticates the optional additional data
.Fa aad
of length
.Fa aad_len ,
and writes the result to
.Fa ciphertext .
.Fa ciphertext_max_len
indicates the space available, which must be at least
.Fa plaintext_len
+
.Dv XAES256GCM_OVERHEAD .
The
.Fa nonce
must be unique for this key.
It does not need to be random or unpredictable; however, random nonces
are allowed.
Reusing a nonce with the same key breaks confidentiality and authenticity.
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_open
verifies the authentication tag in
.Fa ciphertext
and decrypts it.
.Fa plaintext_max_len
indicates the space available, which must be at least
.Fa ciphertext_len
\-
.Dv XAES256GCM_OVERHEAD .
.Fa nonce
and
.Fa aad
must be the same as given to the seal function.
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_seal_kc
is the same as
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_seal
but also appends a 32-byte key commitment tag after the authentication tag.
.Fa ciphertext_max_len
must be at least
.Fa plaintext_len
+
.Dv XAES256GCM_KC_OVERHEAD .
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_open_kc
is the same as
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_open
but also verifies the key commitment.
.Fa plaintext_max_len
must be at least
.Fa ciphertext_len
\-
.Dv XAES256GCM_KC_OVERHEAD .
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_seal ,
.Fn xaes256gcm_open ,
.Fn xaes256gcm_seal_kc ,
and
.Fn xaes256gcm_open_kc
are convenience functions that combine
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_init ,
the corresponding seal or open operation, and
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_destroy
in a single call.
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_rand_nonce
generates a random 24-byte nonce using the CSPRNG.
.Sh RETURN VALUES
All functions, except for
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_destroy ,
return 0 on success or nonzero on error.
.Sh EXAMPLES
This example encrypts and decrypts an ASCII string
"Hello world!" using an all-zero key and a random nonce:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
#include <string.h>
#include <stdio.h>

#include <xaes256gcm.h>

int main(void)
{
    uint8_t key[32] = {0}; // fill with an actual secret key
    uint8_t nonce[24];
    uint8_t plaintext[] = "Hello, world!"; // includes NUL
    uint8_t ciphertext[sizeof(plaintext) - 1 + XAES256GCM_OVERHEAD];
    uint8_t decrypted[sizeof(plaintext)] = {0};
    uint8_t aad[] = "metadata"; // includes NUL

    struct xaes256gcm_ctx c;

    // Initialize context.
    if (xaes256gcm_ctx_init(&c, key) != 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "init failed\en");
        return 1;
    }

    // Generate a random nonce.
    if (xaes256gcm_rand_nonce(nonce) != 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "nonce generation failed\en");
        xaes256gcm_ctx_destroy(&c);
        return 1;
    }

    // Encrypt.
    if (xaes256gcm_ctx_seal(&c, nonce,
            plaintext, sizeof(plaintext) - 1,
            aad, sizeof(aad) - 1,
            ciphertext, sizeof(ciphertext)) != 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "encryption failed\en");
        xaes256gcm_ctx_destroy(&c);
        return 1;
    }

    // Decrypt.
    if (xaes256gcm_ctx_open(&c, nonce,
            ciphertext, sizeof(ciphertext),
            aad, sizeof(aad) - 1,
            decrypted, sizeof(decrypted)) != 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "decryption failed\en");
        xaes256gcm_ctx_destroy(&c);
        return 2;
    }

    printf("%s\en", decrypted); // "Hello, world!"

    xaes256gcm_ctx_destroy(&c);
    return 0;
}
.Ed
.Sh ERRORS
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_init
returns nonzero if the underlying crypto backend failed to initialize.
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_seal ,
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_seal_kc ,
.Fn xaes256gcm_seal ,
.Fn xaes256gcm_seal_kc
return nonzero if the underlying crypto backend failed to encrypt, or if the input
bounds are not satisfied. On error, the state of the resulting ciphertext is
undefined.
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_open ,
.Fn xaes256gcm_ctx_open_kc ,
.Fn xaes256gcm_open ,
.Fn xaes256gcm_open_kc
return nonzero if the underlying crypto backend failed to decrypt, the input bounds
are not satisfied, key commitment verification failed (key-committing variants
only), or ciphertext authentication failed. On error, the resulting plaintext
is undefined and may be overwritten with zeros, but will not contain partially
decrypted data if authentication fails.
.Pp
.Fn xaes256gcm_rand_nonce
returns nonzero if the underlying crypto backend failed to generate random bytes.
